{"format":"tiptap/v1","updatedAt":"2026-06-22T06:38:53.474Z","doc":{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Linear Combinations"},{"type":"text","text":" are the fundamental mathematical operation in forward propagation where each neuron computes a weighted sum of its inputs plus a bias term. This creates the raw signal "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z = WX + b"}},{"type":"text","text":" that is then passed through an activation function."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"What is a Linear Combination?"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Mathematical definition for a single neuron:"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"z = \\sum_{i=1}^{n} w_i x_i + b = w_1 x_1 + w_2 x_2 + \\dots + w_n x_n + b"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Where:\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"x_i"}},{"type":"text","text":" = input values (from previous layer or raw data)\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"w_i"}},{"type":"text","text":" = weights (learned parameters for each input)\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"b"}},{"type":"text","text":" = bias (offset term, also learned)\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"z"}},{"type":"text","text":" = linear combination (raw output before activation)"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Matrix form (for entire layer):"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z = WX + b"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Where:\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z"}},{"type":"text","text":" = matrix of linear combinations for all neurons in layer\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"W"}},{"type":"text","text":" = weight matrix (connections between layers)\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"X"}},{"type":"text","text":" = input matrix (activations from previous layer)\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"b"}},{"type":"text","text":" = bias vector"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[estellenassar](https://www.estellenassar.com/post/neural-networks)"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"How Linear Combinations Work in Forward Propagation"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Step-by-step process:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Step 1: Forward Propagation (Linear Combination)"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Input Layer → Hidden Layer\n   x₁  ──→  ●\n   x₂  ──→  │  Neuron: z = w₁·x₁ + w₂·x₂ + b\n   x₃  ──→  ●"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For each neuron:\n1. Each input is multiplied by its respective weight\n2. All weighted inputs are summed together\n3. Bias term is added\n4. Result = linear combination "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"z"}}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[estellenassar](https://www.estellenassar.com/post/neural-networks)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Step 2: Apply Activation Function (Non-linearity)"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"a = g(z)"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Where:\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"g"}},{"type":"text","text":" = activation function (ReLU, sigmoid, tanh, GELU)\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"a"}},{"type":"text","text":" = activated output (passed to next layer)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Key point"},{"type":"text","text":": The activation function is applied "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"element-wise"},{"type":"text","text":" to each element of "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z"}},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Visual Example: Computing a Linear Combination"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Problem: Single neuron with 3 inputs"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Inputs"},{"type":"text","text":": "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"x = [2.0, 1.5, 3.0]"}}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Weights"},{"type":"text","text":": "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"w = [0.5, -0.3, 0.8]"}}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Bias"},{"type":"text","text":": "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"b = 0.2"}}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Linear combination calculation"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"\\begin{aligned}\nz &= w_1 x_1 + w_2 x_2 + w_3 x_3 + b \\\\\n&= (0.5 \\times 2.0) + (-0.3 \\times 1.5) + (0.8 \\times 3.0) + 0.2 \\\\\n&= 1.0 - 0.45 + 2.4 + 0.2 \\\\\n&= 3.15\n\\end{aligned}"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WP4ERcUsH9E)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Apply activation (ReLU)"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"a = \\operatorname{ReLU}(3.15) = 3.15 \\quad (\\text{positive, so unchanged})"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[estellenassar](https://www.estellenassar.com/post/neural-networks)"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Why Linear Combinations Are Important"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"1. "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Foundation of Neural Network Computation"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Aspect"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Role of Linear Combination"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"rummage signal"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Creates the raw value "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"z"}},{"type":"text","text":" that carries information through network"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Weight learning"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Weights are learned to make linear combinations produce correct outputs"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Layer transformation"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Each layer transforms inputs via linear combination"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[apxml](https://apxml.com/courses/introduction-to-neural-networks/chapter-3-forward-propagation/applying-activations)"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"2. "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Enables Feature Learning"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The weighted sum "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"\\sum w_i x_i"}},{"type":"text","text":" allows the neuron to:\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Emphasize important features"},{"type":"text","text":" (large positive weights)\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Suppress irrelevant features"},{"type":"text","text":" (small or negative weights)\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Combine features"},{"type":"text","text":" (additive combination)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Example"},{"type":"text","text":": In image recognition, a neuron might learn weights that detect \"eyes\" by combining pixel values."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"The Critical Limitation: Why Linear Combinations Alone Are Insufficient"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Key insight:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"If you only use linear combinations without activation functions"},{"type":"text","text":", the entire network behaves like a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"single linear transformation"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"\\text{Network} = W_2(W_1 X + b_1) + b_2 = (W_2 W_1)X + (W_2 b_1 + b_2)"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[apxml](https://apxml.com/courses/introduction-to-neural-networks/chapter-3-forward-propagation/applying-activations)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Which simplifies to:"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"\\text{Network} = W_{\\text{combined}} X + b_{\\text{combined}}"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Consequence"},{"type":"text","text":": No matter how many layers you stack, it's "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"just one linear function"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Why this matters:"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Problem"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Explanation"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Can't model non-linear relationships"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Real data (images, text, complex patterns) is non-linear"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Limited expressiveness"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Can only learn straight lines, planes, hyperplanes"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"No complex pattern learning"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Can't learn curves, boundaries, or intricate structures"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Solution"},{"type":"text","text":": Activation functions introduce "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"non-linearity"},{"type":"text","text":" after each linear combination."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Forward Propagation: The Two-Step Process"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Complete computation within a single layer:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Step 1: Linear Combination"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z^{[l]} = W^{[l]} A^{[l-1]} + b^{[l]}"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Where:\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"l"}},{"type":"text","text":" = current layer number\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"A^{[l-1]}"}},{"type":"text","text":" = activations from previous layer (or input "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"X"}},{"type":"text","text":" for layer 1)\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"W^{[l]}"}},{"type":"text","text":" = weights for layer "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"l"}},{"type":"text","text":"\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"b^{[l]}"}},{"type":"text","text":" = bias for layer "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"l"}},{"type":"text","text":"\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z^{[l]}"}},{"type":"text","text":" = linear combination output"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Step 2: Activation Function"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"A^{[l]} = g^{[l]}(Z^{[l]})"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Where:\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"g^{[l]}"}},{"type":"text","text":" = activation function for layer "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"l"}},{"type":"text","text":"\n- "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"A^{[l]}"}},{"type":"text","text":" = final output (activation) of layer "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"l"}}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"This repeats for all layers"},{"type":"text","text":" until output layer."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[apxml](https://apxml.com/courses/introduction-to-neural-networks/chapter-3-forward-propagation/applying-activations)"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Matrix vs Element-wise Form"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"For a single neuron (element-wise):"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"y = w_1 x_1 + w_2 x_2 + \\dots + w_n x_n + b"}},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"For entire layer (matrix form):"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z = WA + b"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Key difference"},{"type":"text","text":": Matrix form computes linear combinations for "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"all neurons simultaneously"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Linear Combinations in Different Layer Types"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Dense (Fully Connected) Layer:"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z = WX + b"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Each neuron connects to all inputs."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Convolutional Layer:"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z = W \\ast X + b"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Where "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"\\ast"}},{"type":"text","text":" = convolution operation (local linear combination)."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Attention Layer (Transformers):"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z = \\operatorname{softmax}\\left(\\frac{QK^{T}}{\\sqrt{d}}\\right)V"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Where "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"Q = XW_Q"}},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"K = XW_K"}},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"V = XW_V"}},{"type":"text","text":" (all linear combinations)."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[arxiv](https://arxiv.org/html/2301.11360)"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Mental Model: Linear Combination as \"Feature Scoring\""}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Think of a linear combination as calculating a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"weighted score"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Input Features:\n  ├── Age: 30 years    × Weight: 0.5   → Score: 15\n  ├── Income: $50k     × Weight: -0.3  → Score: -15,000\n  ├── Credit: 700      × Weight: 0.8   → Score: 560\n  └── Bias: +10\n\nLinear Combination (Total Score):\n  15 - 15,000 + 560 + 10 = -14,415\n\nActivation (if ReLU):\n  ReLU(-14,415) = 0 (negative → zero)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The weights determine how much each feature contributes to the final score."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Key Takeaways"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Linear combination formula"},{"type":"text","text":": "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"z = \\sum w_i x_i + b"}},{"type":"text","text":" (single neuron) or "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z = WX + b"}},{"type":"text","text":" (layer)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Role in forward propagation"},{"type":"text","text":": First step (weighted sum + bias)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**"},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z"}},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":": Raw output before activation (also called \"pre-activation\" or \"logits\")"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**"},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"W"}},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":": Learned weights that emphasize/suppress features"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**"},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"b"}},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":": Bias offset that shifts decision boundary"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Next step"},{"type":"text","text":": Activation function applied to "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"Z"}},{"type":"text","text":" to introduce non-linearity"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Critical limitation"},{"type":"text","text":": Linear combinations alone = single linear function, regardless of depth"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Why activation needed"},{"type":"text","text":": Without non-linearity, stacking layers doesn't increase expressiveness"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Matrix form"},{"type":"text","text":": Computes all neurons simultaneously (efficient for parallel computation)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Feature learning"},{"type":"text","text":": Weights learn to combine features meaningfully"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Two-step process"},{"type":"text","text":": Linear combination → Activation function (repeats for all layers)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"In Generative AI"},{"type":"text","text":": All Transformers, diffusion models, GANs use this basic computation"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Linear combinations are the core computational operation in neural networks—they create the signal that flows through the network, but require activation functions to enable the non-linear learning that makes deep learning powerful."}]}]}}
